ls – List directories
pwd – Print working directory
cd – Navigate through directories
mkdir – Create directories
mv – Move or rename files
cp – Copy files
rm – Delete files or directories
touch – Create blank/empty files
ln – Create symbolic links (shortcuts)
cat – Display file contents
clear – Clear the terminal display
echo – Print text to terminal
man – Access manual pages for commands
uname – Get basic OS information
whoami – Show active username
tar – Extract and compress files
grep – Search for a string in output
head – Show lines from the top of a file
tail – Show lines from the bottom of a file
export – Export environment variables
zip – Zip files
unzip – Unzip files
ssh – Secure shell access
service – Start/stop services
ps – Display active processes
kill / killall – Terminate processes by ID or name
df – Show disk filesystem info
chmod – Change file permissions
ifconfig – Show network interfaces and IPs
wget – Download files from the internet
ufw – Firewall management
apt / pacman / yum / rpm – Package managers (distro-specific)
sudo – Run commands with elevated privileges
alias – Create custom command shortcuts
whereis – Locate binary, source, and manual pages
whatis – Show what a command does
top – View live processes and system usage
